Flexibility This feature can be used for publishing content such as:
 Online courses Project or software documentation Tutorials  The courses folder may be renamed. For example, we can rename it to docs for software/project documentation or tutorials for creating an online course.
Delete tutorials To remove these pages, delete the courses folder and see below to delete the associated menu link.
Update site menu After renaming or deleting the courses folder, you may wish to update any [[main]] menu links to it by editing your menu configuration at config/_default/menus.toml.
For example, if you delete this folder, you can remove the following from your menu configuration:
[[main]] name = "Courses" url = "courses/" weight = 50  Or, if you are creating a software documentation site, you can rename the courses folder to docs and update the associated Courses menu configuration to:
[[main]] name = "Docs" url = "docs/" weight = 50  Update the docs menu If you use the docs layout, note that the name of the menu in the front matter should be in the form [menu.X] where X is the folder name. Hence, if you rename the courses/example/ folder, you should also rename the menu definitions in the front matter of files within courses/example/ from [menu.example] to [menu.<NewFolderName>].

About Shiny App Recently, I created a Shiny App to access the novel coronavirus’ seasonality. This app was created as part of my unit (ETC5523 Communicating with Data) assessment and also seeks to provide insights of the novel coronavirus seasonality.
The motivation of this app comes amid many speculations especially from health experts around the increased risk of virus spreading in colder seasons. Here in Melbourne, we experienced virus resurgence in winter that dwarfed the 1st outbreak in March. As Europe eases restrictions, for the first time ever, they had a greater number of cases than USA. Besides, many respiratory viruses have a seasonality component that peak in winter (for example people are more prone to flu in winter) and they tend to be more active in winter.
As colder seasons migrate to the Northern hemisphere, we can take this opportunity to consolidate what we learnt from countries in the Southern Hemisphere to potentially anticipate what could happen to the countries in the Northern Hemisphere as many countries seek to reopen their economy.
 Self-Review What was done well I thought the planning phase went well. A lot of thought were put into making an app that is useful and in line with the current situation. I think this planning phase was crucial before any execution could even begin and this is where exploratory Data analysis came into play.
First, I had to look around data (luckily I have gone through some covid-19 data before -see previous blog posts) and see: what could be done & why. Lucky for me, I remembered stumbling upon an twitter post that showed Europe having more cases than USA for the first time *lost the post since. So it gave me the idea start with. So I read more articles about the topic and found articles relating to virus’ seasonality. Hence I thought an app that specifically examines virus’ seasonality would be useful.
Especially since being relatively new to Shiny, I understood that I need to come up with an elaborate plan within my capabilities, knowledge and time frame.
Understanding that covid-19 is affected by numerous factors (not just weather), I decided to use tropical countries as the “baseline” for comparison.
 What can be improved (feasible) I thought the looks of the app could be improved. Even though the creative juices can be running, many of the times I need to think of its feasibility (and my capabilities).
I think the map could be improved. I would prefer a “click-to-show” instead of hovering over the points. In hindsight, using leaflet map could have been a better option with its zooming in and out feature.
Furthermore, I believe that the interactive elements could be improved. For example, connecting the different plots to map or hovering over number of cases that connects to the map to show the number of countries would be neat. Animation on the map to see the different number of cases (with fill colour changing according to a metric e.g. number of cases) in a date range specified by the user would be interesting and useful to examine the covid’s seasonality.
 What can be improved (limited) Clicking on a country on the map provides a walkthrough of latest relevant news on covid and a brief summary of its latest happenings (could be a little far fetched)

 Overview of Coronavirus cases in the world’s most stringent lockdown country The first case of coronavirus in Philippines was recorded on 30th January 2020. Philippines was the first country outside of China to record a confirmed death from the virus (Austin and Tiffany (2020)). They did not see another case for a month before it met its first local transmission on March 7 as reported on CNN (2020).
Since then, the virus has been spread to every region around Phillipines. (you might want to play around with interactive region plot below!). With a surge in cases, in about 10 days, what has been touted the “strictest coronavirus lockdown in the world” was enforced. With the President ordered to “shoot dead” whoever who defied the lockdown; emulating Philippines tactics in the drug war Philippines was still recovering from. (Capatides (2020)) Involving house to house visits, a mandated 8pm-5am curfew extending to over 60million people, deploying army and police to man checkpoints.(Coronel (2020)).

Background Iran is one of if not the worse-hit country in the world from the covid-19 pandemic. It was the first country in Middle East to come into contact with the virus when it officially announced with 2 deaths from the virus on 19 February 2020.
This pandemic could not arrive at a worse time. It coincided with country’s parliamentary election and also 1979 Islamic revolution- its reputation was (and still is) at stake.
Furthermore, their economy was in turmoil even before the outbreak, as tough sanctions progressively tightened as part of Trump’s administration’s “maximum pressure strategy” after US withdrew from international nuclear agreement with Iran. This drastically drained Iran’s ability to access medical and healthcare supplies to combat the virus, urging Iran appeal for a $5 billion emergency loan from International Monetary Fund(IMF). This also implicated its testing capabilities and inadequate testing kits; having only few labs to obtain test results, it delayed testing extensively.
All these amid rising political tensions nationally and internationally. In November 2019, the oil-rich country faced an unprecedented oil price hike and widespread protests were ravaging the country while the demand for oil decreases. In January 2020, Iran had to deal with US assassination of top Iranian general and mistake of firing missle at Ukrainian airliner.
These are sensitive and crucial times for the government. Tough decisions needs to made as Iran faces the pandemic in the busiest period of the year (Iranian New Year). As Iran soon become the epicenter of the virus, many criticisms arise that the government incentivized for not being transparent in updating the local situation to the locals and rest of the world amid data leak. Iran had started off with the highest mortality rate outside China.
With lifting of restrictions lurking in the talks, I think it is reasonable to doubt if it is premature as the economy cannot sustain any longer or the government is playing down the situation. We might better understand how the virus unfolded given some data.
 Data Description Data serves to facilitate data exploration into Iran’s critical situation motivated by lack of studies conducted.
Virus containment & measures These 2 tables are looks at the related to the effect of the virus but also the government measures implemented to combat the virus. The data sources comes from John Hopkins University CSSE (widely considered the standard resource for researchers & general audience) and Assessmenet Capacities Project (ACAPS) respectively. These variables are smoothly selected from and accessible via tidycovid19 package.

Create slides in Markdown with Academic  Academic | Documentation
 Features  Efficiently write slides in Markdown 3-in-1: Create, Present, and Publish your slides Supports speaker notes Mobile friendly slides   Controls  Next: Right Arrow or Space Previous: Left Arrow Start: Home Finish: End Overview: Esc Speaker notes: S Fullscreen: F Zoom: Alt + Click  PDF Export: E   Code Highlighting Inline code: variable
Code block:
porridge = "blueberry" if porridge == "blueberry": print("Eating...")   Math In-line math: $x + y = z$
Block math:
$$ f\left( x \right) = ;\frac{{2\left( {x + 4} \right)\left( {x - 4} \right)}}{{\left( {x + 4} \right)\left( {x + 1} \right)}} $$
 Fragments Make content appear incrementally
{{% fragment %}} One {{% /fragment %}} {{% fragment %}} **Two** {{% /fragment %}} {{% fragment %}} Three {{% /fragment %}}  Press Space to play!
One  Two  Three 
 A fragment can accept two optional parameters:
 class: use a custom style (requires definition in custom CSS) weight: sets the order in which a fragment appears   Speaker Notes Add speaker notes to your presentation
{{% speaker_note %}} - Only the speaker can read these notes - Press `S` key to view {{% /speaker_note %}}  Press the S key to view the speaker notes!
 Only the speaker can read these notes Press S key to view    Themes  black: Black background, white text, blue links (default) white: White background, black text, blue links league: Gray background, white text, blue links beige: Beige background, dark text, brown links sky: Blue background, thin dark text, blue links    night: Black background, thick white text, orange links serif: Cappuccino background, gray text, brown links simple: White background, black text, blue links solarized: Cream-colored background, dark green text, blue links   Custom Slide Customize the slide style and background
{{< slide background-image="/media/boards.jpg" >}} {{< slide background-color="#0000FF" >}} {{< slide class="my-style" >}}   Custom CSS Example Let’s make headers navy colored.
Create assets/css/reveal_custom.css with:
.reveal section h1, .reveal section h2, .reveal section h3 { color: navy; }   Questions?  Ask
